                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.11L5232/590: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-06-05T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 5, 1936—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>67. Your 169, June 4, 2 p.m. You may inform Pfeffer informally that your
                    Government is prepared to send a representative to Germany to discuss the
                    sabotage cases, but that it assumes it is to await an indication from the German
                    Foreign Office that such a visit is desired, as Commission has set hearing for
                    June 17 to determine further procedure. Meanwhile preparations are being made to
                    act immediately upon receipt of such an indication. You should inquire whether
                    Goering will arrange the matter with the Foreign Office or whether he desires
                    that you should make inquiry.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
